# 1. Introduction
1. The flow past a surface-mounted bluff body is characterized by ~={purple}the formation of U-shaped necklace vortices=~ that wrap around its upstream base, ~={purple}separated shear layers (SSLs)=~ on its sides and ~={purple}a wake extending downstream=~.
2. The system of coherent necklace vortices forming at ~={purple}the junction between the bluff body and the bottom surface=~ under the influence of adverse pressure gradients is referred as the horseshoe vortex (HV) system.
## A. Laminar horseshoe vortex system
1. The separation of the incoming (upstream) boundary layer and the formation of a ~={purple}separation=~ (stagnation) ~={purple}line =~on the bottom surface around the cylinder are a consequence of the~={purple} adverse pressure gradients =~induced by the surface-mounted cylinder.
	1. The reorganization of the boundary-layer vorticity downstream of the ~={purple}separation line=~ results in the formation of a system of coherent necklace vortices.
2. ~={red}The main necklace vortices of the HV system=~ have the same sense of rotation as the vorticity in the upstream boundary layer.
	1. These vortices interact with the channel bed and induce the formation of additional ~={purple}bottom-attached vortices (BAVs)=~.
3. Due to the ~={purple}adverse pressure gradients=~, the necklace vortices originating in the separation region stretch around the cylinder and fold around the upstream part of it, very close to the channel bottom.
	1. The sides of the vortex lines become oriented in the streamwise direction, with the vorticity being of opposite sense in the two sides (~={purple}legs of the necklace vortices=~).
4. The HV system can be laminar or turbulent.
	1. Previous studies of laminar junction flows (e.g., see ~={purple}Baker=~,[8] ~={purple}Thomas=~,[9] ~={purple}Seal et al.=~,[10], [11] ~={purple}Simpson=~,[1] ~={purple}Lin et al.=~[12]) have shown that the structure of the HV system and the dynamics of the necklace vortices depend primarily on the ~={purple}cylinder Reynolds number, ReD=~, and ~={purple}the characteristics of the incoming boundary layer=~.
		1. Laminar vs. Turbulent
		2. Ratio between ~={purple}the displacement thickness of the incoming boundary layer at the location of the cylinder=~ and the cylinder width or diameter, $\delta^{*}/D$
	2. The coherence and evolution of the HV system is also affected by ~={purple}the shape of the cylinder=~.
		1. Circular vs. Rectangular
		2. Relative bluntness of the upstream part of the cylinder
		3. Width to height aspect ratio
5. Most investigations (e.g., see ~={purple}Greco=~,[13] ~={purple}Seal et al.=~[11]) classify the laminar HV system into ~={cyan}five main sub-regimes.=~
	1. In the ~={red}~={cyan}*steady sub-regime*=~=~, one or several steady necklace vortices are present.
	2. The number of vortices increases with the value of $Re_{D}$.[8], [14], [15]
	3. At a sufficiently high Reynolds number, the HV system becomes unsteady.
		1. The critical value of the $Re$ depends strongly on the characteristics of the incoming boundary layer, e.g., the ratio $\delta^{*}/D$
			1.  ~={purple}Thomas=~,[9] : the critical Reynolds number was only 1000 and the dependency on δ*/D was much reduced compared to other authors.
			2. ~={purple}Wei et al.=~[15] : the critical Reynolds number was around 2000.
6. As the HV system becomes unsteady, the necklace vortices start oscillating back and forth over a small distance, ~={red}but do not interact =~(e.g., do not exchange vorticity).
	1. The frequency of oscillation increases with $Re_{D}$
	2. This sub-regime, which is called ~={cyan}*the oscillating sub-regime*=~, was observed for $1700 < Re_{D} < 1900$ in the experiments of Greco[13]
7. As the Reynolds number is further increased, necklace vortices ~={red}start being shed periodically=~ from the region where the incoming boundary layer separates, regardless of the value of $\delta^{*}/D$.
	1. The structure of the HV system changes to one in which the ~={purple}primary vortex=~, which is situated at all times closest to the cylinder, breaks away from the formation region.Then, the ~={purple}primary vortex=~ moves toward the obstacle, but a certain point is drawn back toward the formation region. There it encounters a new vortex that was shed from the formation region and eventually merges with it to form ~={purple}the new primary vortex=~.
		1. This regime was present up to $ReD ∼= 2500$in the experiments of ~={purple}Greco=~[13] and is called the ~={cyan}*amalgamating sub-regime*=~.
			1. In many experimental investigations, this sub-regime was not observed[12]
8. A further increase of the Reynolds number induces transition to ~={cyan}*the breakaway sub-regime*=~.
	1. The structure of the HV system in this sub-regime is ~={red}characterized by the presence of three main co-rotating vortices.=~ The so-called ~={purple}developing vortex=~ is the vortex that is shed from the separation region. The ~={purple}primary vortex=~ is situated in between the developing vortex and the ~={purple}corner vortex=~; and the ~={purple}corner vortex=~ is situated close to the cylinder’s upstream face. 
	2. As the developing vortex breaks away from the formation region, it becomes the new primary vortex. Meanwhile, ~={red}the primary vortex moves toward the cylinder and eventually merges with the original corner vortex=~, becoming ~={purple}the new corner vortex=~.
		1. This sub-regime was studied by ~={purple}Seal et al.=~[10], [11] and ~={purple}Lin et al.=~[12] for rectangular cylinders. At a certain point (e.g., $Re_{D} \sim 4750$ in the experiments of ~={purple}Greco=~,[13] $Re_{D} = 4700–6000$ depending on the value of $\delta^{*}/D$ in the experiments of ~={purple}Lin et al.=~[26])
	3. the coherence of the necklace vortices breaks down. The HV system starts displaying a transitional behavior. This ~={cyan}*transitional sub-regime*=~ covers the transition from the laminar to the turbulent regime which is completed around $Re_{D} = 14000$.[15]

## B Near-wake region
1. The flow past infinitely long cylinders was studied extensively over recent decades.[16]
2.  Attached boundary layers on the cylinder are laminar at separation and the Reynolds number is high enough (ReD >1000), the ~={purple}Kelvin-Helmholtz instabilities=~ in the ~={purple}SSLs=~ grow into eddies (vortex tubes) that are shed at a frequency that is strongly dependent on ReD. This frequency is independent of the one associated with the shedding of roller vortices (~={purple}von Karman vortex street=~) in the wake of the bluff body. In
	1. In the case of an infinitely long cylinder, the axes of the vortex tubes are close to parallel to the axis of the cylinder. The flow transitions in the downstream part of the SSLs. The wake flow is turbulent.
	2. In the case of finite-length cylinders, end disturbances in the spanwise (relative to the cylinder) direction (e.g., the presence of a free surface or of a solid wall at one end of the cylinder) induce strong disturbances along the axes of the vortex tubes and trigger what is generally called ~={purple}oblique shedding=~.[16]
3. Experiments[4], [17] have shown that t~={purple}he limited vertical extent of the water depth=~ in the channel can play an important role in the development of the turbulent wake downstream of the surface-mounted cylinder.
	1. As the ratio between ~={purple}the width (diameter) of the obstacle, D=~, and ~={purple}the flow depth, H=~, increases, the effects of the bottom friction on the development and vortical structure of the wake flow become more important.
4. Chen and Jirka4, 18 related the presence of absolute (or global) and convective instabilities (see Huerre and Monkewitz19) to the formation or absence of large-scale rollers in the near wake of a cylinder placed in a shallow channel.















